attributes.title: OPR_Text_DebuggerConnected
attributes.visState: {"title":"OPR_Text_DebuggerConnected","type":"markdown","aggs":[],"params":{"fontSize":12,"openLinksInNewTab":false,"markdown":"## Application debugging\n\nThis table shows the **number of attempts to attach a debugger** to the application. Attackers are often using debuggers to gain insights about application inner workings. Observing and manipulating an app during runtime makes it much, much easier to decipher its behavior. They can then use this knowledge to attack the application or its users."}}

attributes.title: OPR_Text_Emulator
attributes.visState: {"title":"OPR_Text_Emulator","type":"markdown","aggs":[],"params":{"fontSize":12,"openLinksInNewTab":false,"markdown":"## Dynamic analysis\n\nDynamic analysis tests the mobile app by executing and running the app binary and analysing its workflows for vulnerabilities, business logic flaws, or weak input validation. In dynamic analysis, you can easily spot what information is stored persistently and if the information is protected properly. Running an application inside an emulator/simulator allows an attacker to hook or trace program execution. For applications running inside an emulator, it is easy to inspect the state of the system, reset it to a saved image, or monitor how the app operates."}}

attributes.title: OPR_Text_Tamper
attributes.visState: {"title":"OPR_Text_Tamper","type":"markdown","aggs":[],"params":{"fontSize":12,"openLinksInNewTab":false,"markdown":"## Application modification\n\nThis table shows the **number of modified applications installed on user devices**. Every application can be easily modified and then resigned by an attacker. This process is known as application *repackaging*. There may be many reasons for application repackaging whether it's the addition of new code, removal of app protections or bypassing app licensing."}}

attributes.title: XMSN_Text_Tamper_UnofficialStore
attributes.visState:
{"title":"XMSN_Text_Tamper_UnofficialStore","type":"markdown","aggs":[],"params":{"fontSize":12,"openLinksInNewTab":false,"markdown":"## Application cloning

The visualisation shows the number of devices on which the app integrity event happened. Modified/tampered application is often distributed using third party stores or other side channels. This would result in an increasing number of devices, on which would be the tampered application installed.

## Unofficial Store
The number of devices with applications installed from unofficial store is also included in the visualisations. This might mean that someone has copied an app and is now distributing its potentially malicious copy."}}

attributes.title: OPR_Text_Hooks
attributes.visState: {"title":"OPR_Text_Hooks","type":"markdown","aggs":[],"params":{"fontSize":12,"openLinksInNewTab":false,"markdown":"## Code injection and modification\n\nThis table shows the number of **reverse engineering attempts** or **loaded dynamic libraries**, and **8 most affected devices**. The application can be analysed or modified even though its source code has not been changed through a technique known as hooking. This technique can be used to intercept system or application calls and then modify them. An attacker can exploit this by inserting new or modifying existing code to obtain personal client data or to insert malicious code into an application. The most well-known hooking frameworks are Frida, Xposed or Cydia Substrate."}}

attributes.visState: {"title":"XMSN_Text_HwBackedKeychain_iOS","type":"markdown","aggs":[],"params":{"fontSize":12,"openLinksInNewTab":false,"markdown":"**Hw-backed keychain**\n--------------------------------\nThe visualisations show the ratio of devices with and without hw-backed keychain, and the types of keychain the device use/don't use. Hw-backed keychain stores cryptographic keys in separate hardware, to make their extraction nonviable. **Secure Enclave** is a dedicated secure subsystem integrated into Apple SoCs. attributes.title: DPA_Text_HwBackedKeystore
attributes.visState:
{"title":"DPA_Text_HwBackedKeystore","type":"markdown","aggs":[],"params":{"fontSize":12,"openLinksInNewTab":false,"markdown":"**Hw-backed keystore**
--------------------------------
The visualisations show the ratio of devices with and without hw-backed keystore, and the types of keystores the device use/don't use. Hw-backed keystore stores cryptographic keys in separate hardware, to make their extraction nonviable. Devices not using hw-backed keystore are more prone to extraction of user keys.
**Trusted execution environment (TEE)** is a secure area of a main processor with it's own OS, which communicates with the Android OS through a restricted interface and thus making the processes running in the TEE more secure.
**StrongBox** is newer and more secure than TEE. Keys in StrongBox are stored in a Secure Element (SE) - a separate microchip with it's own CPU, storage and other resources.
"}}

Biometrics are unique to an user what makes them more secure compared to e.g. passcode, which could be known by an unauthorised user. Some examples of frequently used biometrics are fingerprints or facial patterns."}}
